{"id":"2104.06767","submitter":"Gabriel Schnoering","authors":"Maximilian Gill, Bruno Gompf, Martin Dressel and Gabriel Schnoering","title":"Equivalence of light transport and depolarization","comments":"5 pages, 4 figures, 1 table and 2 Supplementary Notes","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.105.053511","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.optics","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  The study of scattered polarized light has led to important advances in\ndistinct fields such as astronomy, atmospheric sciences and bio-imaging. In\nrandom diffusing media, light disorientation and the scrambling of its\npolarization state appear to always occur together. Their apparent\ninseparability suggests a profound connection between optical transport and\ndepolarization. Here, we present experimental evidence of their equivalence and\nquantify their relationship in colloidal suspensions of microscopic\nconstituents. In particular, a proportionality relation between optical\ntransport lengths and their depolarization counterparts is provided. This\nequivalence imposes depolarization whenever light traverses random media and\nholds for wide spectral ranges and scatterer concentrations. Our results\nclarify the connection between microscopic processes and measurable\npolarization signatures.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 14 Apr 2021 10:47:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-05-16"}
