{"id":"2104.06864","submitter":"Yuanfei Huang","authors":"Yuanfei Huang and Qiao Huang and Jinqiao Duan","title":"The Most Probable Transition Paths of Stochastic Dynamical Systems: A\n  Sufficient and Necessary Characterization","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The most probable transition path of a stochastic dynamical system is the\nglobal minimizer of the Onsager-Machlup action functional in a path space, and\ncan be described by a sufficient but not necessary condition, the\nEuler-Lagrange equation (a second order differential equation with\ninitial-terminal conditions) from a variational principle. This work is devoted\nto show a sufficient and necessary characterization for the most probable\ntransition paths of stochastic dynamical systems with Brownian noise. We prove\nthat, under appropriate conditions, the most probable transition path(s) is\n(are) completely determined by a first order ordinary differential equation.\nThe equivalence is established by showing that the Onsager-Machlup action\nfunctional of the original system can be derived from the corresponding\nMarkovian bridge process. For linear stochastic systems and the nonlinear\nHongler's model, the first order differential equations determining most\nprobable transition paths are shown numerically to be equivalent to\nEuler-Lagrange equations of the Onsager-Machlup functional. For general\nnonlinear systems, the determining first order differential equations can be\napproximated, in short time or for small noise case, in a way that is more\nefficient than Euler-Lagrange equations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 14 Apr 2021 13:56:31 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 8 Oct 2021 17:26:51 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 29 Oct 2021 13:30:27 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Sat, 11 Jun 2022 16:47:37 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Wed, 28 Dec 2022 20:09:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-01-02"}
{"id":"2104.06865","submitter":"Shengqiang Li","authors":"Shengqiang Li, Menglong Xu, Xiao-Lei Zhang","title":"Efficient conformer-based speech recognition with linear attention","comments":"submitted to APSIPA ASC 2021","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.SD eess.AS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Recently, conformer-based end-to-end automatic speech recognition, which\noutperforms recurrent neural network based ones, has received much attention.\nAlthough the parallel computing of conformer is more efficient than recurrent\nneural networks, the computational complexity of its dot-product self-attention\nis quadratic with respect to the length of the input feature. To reduce the\ncomputational complexity of the self-attention layer, we propose multi-head\nlinear self-attention for the self-attention layer, which reduces its\ncomputational complexity to linear order. In addition, we propose to factorize\nthe feed forward module of the conformer by low-rank matrix factorization,\nwhich successfully reduces the number of the parameters by approximate 50% with\nlittle performance loss. The proposed model, named linear attention based\nconformer (LAC), can be trained and inferenced jointly with the connectionist\ntemporal classification objective, which further improves the performance of\nLAC. To evaluate the effectiveness of LAC, we conduct experiments on the\nAISHELL-1 and LibriSpeech corpora. Results show that the proposed LAC achieves\nbetter performance than 7 recently proposed speech recognition models, and is\ncompetitive with the state-of-the-art conformer. Meanwhile, the proposed LAC\nhas a number of parameters of only 50% over the conformer with faster training\nspeed than the latter.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 14 Apr 2021 13:56:32 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 23 Jul 2021 13:02:57 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-07-26"}
